Classification.Comment: Trisomy of the terminal 1q arm is a rare event. Distal duplications of the long arm of chromosome 1 have been reported in patients with intellectual disability, developmental delay, and facial dysmorphism. In addition, mild cardiac defects were common, such as atrial septald efects, ventricular septal defects, and mild aortic regurgitation. Recurrent respiratory tract infections and anomalies of the central nervous and urogenital systems (mainly inguinal hernias and cryptorchidism) were also often observed (Mol Syndromol. 2016 Feb;6(6):297-303. PMID: 27022331; Am J Med Genet A. 2016 Apr;170A(4):908-17. PMID: 26782913).
